Airel in La Manche, Normandy. Compare   Dorrell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorrell","meanings":["English (mainly Worcestershire): variant of   Darrell  ."]},{"name":"Dural","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Darrell  .","Turkish: ornamental name or nickname from <i>dural</i> ‘always the same’."]}]},{"name":"Marmaduke","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain derivation. It is generally held to be an Anglicized form of the Old Irish name <i>Mael-Maedóc</i> ‘devotee of Maedóc’. The name <i>Maedóc</i> was borne by various early Irish saints, most notably a 6th-century abbot of Clonmore and a 7th-century bishop of Ferns.  Mael-Maedóc Ó Morgair  (  1095–1148 ) was a reformer of the Church in Ireland and a friend of Bernard of Clairvaux. However, the modern Gaelic form (from  <i>c.</i>1200 ) is <i>Maol-Maodhóg</i> (pronounced ‘mul-<b>may</b>-og’), so that the name would have had to have been borrowed into English before this loss of the <i>d</i>. <i>Marmaduke</i> has never been common except in Yorkshire, where for example it was bourne by  Marmaduke Huby , abbot of Fountains, (  1495–1526 ). Its most notable bearer in recent times has been  Marmaduke Hussey  (  1923–2006 ), a former chairman of the governors of the BBC."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Marmaduke de Darrell of Sessay was born about 1244, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William Darrel, was 28 and his mother, Ada de Percy, was 20. He married Helenisa De Insula. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1283, in Thirsk, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1244–1283":"umbes 1244–1283","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1244–1283":"1244–1283","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud"